### Installation
helm repo add bitnami https://charts.bitnami.com/bitnami
helm repo update
helm install sample bitnami/kafka \
     --set volumePermissions.enabled=true \
     --set zookeeper.volumePermissions.enabled=true

### INFO

NAME: kafka
LAST DEPLOYED: Tue Sep 21 20:32:58 2021
NAMESPACE: test
STATUS: deployed
REVISION: 1
TEST SUITE: None
NOTES:
** Please be patient while the chart is being deployed **

Kafka can be accessed by consumers via port 9092 on the following DNS name from within your cluster:

    kafka.test.svc.cluster.local

Each Kafka broker can be accessed by producers via port 9092 on the following DNS name(s) from within your cluster:

    kafka-0.kafka-headless.test.svc.cluster.local:9092

To create a pod that you can use as a Kafka client run the following commands:

    kubectl run kafka-client --restart='Never' --image docker.io/bitnami/kafka:2.8.1-debian-10-r0 --namespace test --command -- sleep infinity
    kubectl exec --tty -i kafka-client --namespace test -- bash

    PRODUCER:
        kafka-console-producer.sh \
            
            --broker-list kafka-0.kafka-headless.test.svc.cluster.local:9092 \
            --topic test

    CONSUMER:
        kafka-console-consumer.sh \
            
            --bootstrap-server kafka.test.svc.cluster.local:9092 \
            --topic test \
            --from-beginning

### Running Busybox
kcdebug() { kubectl run -i --rm --tty debug --image=busybox --restart=Never -- sh --namespace $1}
podName() { kubectl -n $1 get pod | grep $2 | awk '{ print $1 }' }